    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-07T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-07T16:00:00-05:00" n="651"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d651">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">561.333D3/1606: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-07T18:00:00-03:00"
                            >December 7, 1943—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5622. Private sources report that 8600 bags and 25,600 bags of new crop coffee
                    (reference Embassy’s telegram No. 5596, December 4, 3 p.m.)<note n="98"
                        xml:id="d651fn98">Not printed; it indicated that there was sufficient coffee
                        on hand at Santos to fill the tonnage assigned (561.333D3/1605).</note>
                    arrived at Santos on December 6 and December 7 respectively, as against Guedes’
                    recent assurances to the Minister of Finance and Embassy that entries would
                    total 40,000 bags daily.</p>
                <p>Reports from Santos indicate that sales of new crop coffee for shipment to the
                    United States are very quiet due to the rumors that American importers will
                    receive a subsidy of 5 cents per pound and that they will be permitted to
                    increase prices correspondingly.</p>
                <p>Have importers in the United States noticed any improvement in sales or prices of
                    Brazil’s new crop coffee?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
